= Literature Review

The literature review is an essential requirement of any academic project. A comprehensive review of the literature will provide background to the project, and should be used to inform a set of requirements that your solution must meet. It also establishes that what you have done is the result of academic study, rather than an unfounded whim. This should be a coherent, critical evaluation of relevant academic literature with clear linkage to your project.

It may be helpful to break up this chapter into sections, with each focused on a different topic or aspect of the project. At MSc level, you are expected to provide a comprehensive and insightful review, with an impressive degree of critical evaluation that clearly informs the final outcomes of the project.

== The Research Gap

Having reviewed the literature, you should identify a clear gap in knowledge or practice that your project addresses. This section should synthesise the evidence from your review and articulate the specific problem or opportunity that motivates your work.

== Aim and Objectives

Having situated your project within a body of relevant literature, you should now be in a position to state your aims and objectives. Most projects will have one aim that is a broad statement of what the project will achieve. The objectives should be statements of how that aim will be achieved. Objectives should be Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Realistic and Time-related (SMART).

=== Aim

State the overarching aim of your project in a single, clear sentence.

=== Objectives

List your SMART objectives here. These should be concrete, measurable steps that collectively achieve the aim.

=== Research Questions and Hypotheses

If your project involves a user study or empirical research, you should state your research questions here. If appropriate, you may also state formal hypotheses. Research questions should flow naturally from the research gap identified above.
